column1: Raised primarily in Grundy, Virginia, and an alumnus of Radford University, Mays is an American actress best known for playing Emma Pillsbury on the hit musical comedy-drama series Glee (2009-2015) and Charlie Andrews on the NBC superhero drama series Heroes (2006-2010). She is also known for her starring roles in Wes Craven’s psychological thriller film Red Eye (2005), Paul Blart: Mall Cop (2009), and The Smurfs (2011). For Glee, Mays won a Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series in 2010. #VPA #VFO #JaymaMays #Glee #Heroes #ScreenActorsGuild

column1: Who Says You Need an Automotive Background to Run a Successful Shop http://bit.ly/2v7Qcdi:=:https://remarkableresults.biz/a115/ Now visit with Brian Sump from Avalon Motorsports and Andy Bizub from Midwest Performance Cars as they share their strategy for growing their business. This is an interview like no other you’ve heard here on Remarkable Results or the Town Hall Academy for that matter. This interview should open your eyes because Brian and Andy did not grow up in the business. They were not technicians with a dream of owning their own shop. They share their strategies and tactics that have shaped their continuing success. Brian and Andy basically became the CEO of their business. We talk about that a lot on the podcast. column1: Spreading awareness about the tragedy occurring along the border in Ciudad Juarez, Mexico is Imperative Entertainment's first English and Spanish language podcast The Red Note (La Nota Roja), which examines the story of the Juarez femicides through the voices of investigators who have tried to solve the mystery of these crimes. The investigation into these crimes has revealed a systemic web of corruption, drug violence, sex trafficking, and unchecked globalization that authorities have tried desperately to hide. Join us, as we listen and learn every Tuesday when a new episode drops. Click one of the links below or find The Red Note (English) or La Nota Roja (Spanish) on Apple Podcasts or wherever you get shows. column1: Eyes attended the “Drive for 45” motorcade on Sunday, October 25, 2020. The group met at Turkey Brook Park at 4:00PM for speeches, prayer & song before departing on a rolling rally through the streets of Mount Olive, NJ. Gregory Lucas, a singer, delivered a moving presentation of th national anthem. Veteran and Flanders resident, Rafael Ruggiero, prayed for his country and his president. The Young Patriots leaded the pledge of allegiance for the crowd. Mount Olive councilman, Alex Roman, expressed his concerns for the former president and black lives matter. Shortly before 5:00PM, Mount Olive Township Police led the motorcade departing Turkey Brook Park. Two large decommissioned military trucks joined the parade of cars, trucks, motorcycles, vans, convertibles, SUVs, crossovers, coupes & small busses. A gentleman in a mid-2000s Ford Explorer bellowed “fake news” coupled with an odd glare to John Edmunds IV of #EyesOnNJ News. Event organizers, Mt. Olive Patriots, asked attendees to bring one-canned good per vehicle for the Mount Olive Food Pantry. Eyes caught up with Sue Morse, director of the Mount Olive Food Pantry, who expressed thanks towards the Trump Rally attendees and advised that the pantry is open to anyone who worships, works, or lives in Mount Olive. column1: If you know me well you know it’s very rare if I’m drinking coffee but I’ve been up since 2AM (thank you anxiety) and could not fall back asleep so naturally I stopped for some much needed caffeine on my way to work today. When I got to the window I was informed the driver in front of me paid for my coffee & it turned my whole day around. It’s like God knew I needed a little pick me up. I #paiditforward to the driver behind me & I hope the gesture continued multiple cars after. It’s the little things ♥️
